The '''string jelyfish''', '''''Apolemia uvaria''''', also known as the '''barbed wire jellyfish''', is a [[siphonophore]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Apolemiidae]].<ref name="worms1">http://marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=135497 accessed 8 September 2013</ref>

==Description==
String jellyfish are colonial animals which may reach 3m in total lenth and have a diameter of 2-5cm. The colony is formed of a central string bearing groups of pink and white tentacles which clump together or extend. The whole colony has a gas float at the front and a set of swimming bells. <ref name="Wrobel">Wrobel D. & Mills C. 2003. ''Pacific Coast Pelagic Invertebrates'': a guide to the common gelatinous animals. Sea Challengers. ISBN 0-930118-23-5</ref>

==Distribution==
This colonial animal is [[pelagic]] and is found in oceans worldwide in midwater.<ref name="Wrobel"/>

==Ecology==
These ocean predators act like drift nets, spreading their tentacles to catch plankton. The tentacles give a painful sting and are best avoided.<ref name="Wrobel"/>


